         <abstract>
            <p>A uniform asymptotic approximation which can be used for all $qh \geqslant 0$ is developed for the Fourier integral $$I(h) = \int^z_q \frac{f(\sqrt{y^2 - q^2)}{(y^2 - q^2)^1/2} \sin yh dy$$ under the assumptions that $hz &gt;&gt; 1$, that the first $L + 2$ derivatives of $f(y)$ are continuous for $0 \leqslant y \leqslant (z^2 - q^2)^{1/2}$, and that the first $2L + 2$ derivatives of $f(y)$ are continuous at $y = 0$. The approximation is especially convenient when $z &gt;&gt; q$.</p>
          </abstract>
